{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505979"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:38:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:38:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2502"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2502"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.02,0.52,0.37]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2502"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53390"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2502"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2502"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38845"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"571"},{"type":"tags","id":"1302"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2313"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2351"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15242"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42513"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53390"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman is brought into the Emergency Department by ambulance after intentionally ingesting fifty tablets of immediate-release paracetamol (500mg each) approximately five hours ago. According to the mother, who phoned for an ambulance after finding her daughter vomiting next to the empty medication packets, the daughter recently broke up with her boyfriend and has been experiencing troubles at work. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medication. On examination her pulse rate is 75/min, blood pressure 120/70mmHg, and respiratory rate 14/min. Her GCS is 15 and there is no evidence of jaundice or asterixis. She weighs 60kg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate course of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activated charcoal","Observation only","Referral to gastroenterology for admission and monitoring","Urgent serum paracetamol levels","N-acetylcysteine infusion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has ingested fifty 500mg tablets of paracetamol, making a total ingestion dose of 25g. A toxic dose of paracetamol that may be associated with acute liver injury is \u2265200mg/kg or \u226510g (whichever of these is lower). As such, any patient who ingests 10g or more (such as in this case) is automatically considered to have been exposed to a toxic dose and is at risk of acute liver injury. Management of paracetamol overdose is heavily protocolised through toxicology guidelines, which relies on several key components - dose taken, the formulation of paracetamol (immediate versus modified release), time since ingestion and serum drug levels. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivated charcoal \u003C/strong\u003Eis recommended if the patient presents within two hours of ingesting \u2265200mg/kg or \u226510g of paracetamol. For paracetamol ingestions \u226530g, activated charcoal can be administered up to four hours after ingestion. This patient ingested the tablets five hours ago, so activated charcoal is not recommended in these circumstances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn cases of toxic paracetamol ingestion, the main factor that determines whether to commence \u003Cstrong\u003EN-acetylcysteine\u003C/strong\u003E before or after \u003Cstrong\u003Echecking serum paracetamol levels \u003C/strong\u003Eis the time elapsed following ingestion\u003Cem\u003E. \u003C/em\u003EFor patients who have ingested 4-8 hours ago, the management consists of (1) checking paracetamol levels and (2) initiating treatment with N-acetylcysteine if levels are above the treatment line on the nomogram chart. For patients who have ingested more than 8 hours ago, the management consists of (1) empirical N-acetylcysteine infusion and (2) checking serum paracetamol levels and ALT. If paracetamol levels are below the treatment line on the nomogram and ALT levels \u226450 U/L, N-acetylcysteine therapy can be ceased.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the case of this patient, she falls in the category of 4-8 hours post-ingestion, as she ingested 5 hours ago. As such, checking paracetamol levels is the correct answer. If these levels are above the treatment line, it is then that N-acetylcysteine should be commenced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E It will be essential to assay her \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum paracetamol levels.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to gastroenterology for admission and monitoring \u003C/strong\u003Emight be correct, but only once baseline investigations and appropriate management have been initiated in the emergency department. As such, referral onwards is not the most immediate next step in her management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation alone \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be inappropriate given the dose ingested.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In cases of paracetamol overdose, check blood levels of the drug will help determine treatment."],"references":["Chiew AL, Reith D, Pomerleau A, Wong A, Isoardi KZ, Soderstrom J, et al. Updated guidelines for the management of paracetamol poisoning in Australia and New Zealand. Med J Aust. 2020;212(4):175\u201383. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31786822/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38845"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2502"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38845"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-20T09:57:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-20T09:58:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2502"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53390"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpretin